 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://hem.bredband.net/mikahr/Tinwinsig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=karnosdarkmere>Karnos Darkmere</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/8/03 4:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Looking for new authors</span><hr size=1> Julian May.  An adult writer for an adult audience.  Her Saga of the Pliocene Exile--mingling elements of both fantasy and science fiction with a keen understanding of human nature and a breathtaking mastery of the language--remains my favorite written work to date.<br>
<br>
Everything written by Guy Gavriel Kay, really.  If you don't like sentimental writing, however, this may not be for you.  Some of his best:  The Fionavar Tapestry (trilogy); Tignana; A Song for Arbonne.  Deeply touching fantasy.<br>
<br>
Roger Zelazny, The Chronicles of Amber (five books).  The tale of a hard-boiled, dryly witty, cynical prince cast as hero in a world of power, intrigue, and passion.  Even after almost thirty years, this remains one of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> capital works of fantasy.  Before his death, Zelazny won the Hugo and Nebula Awards several times for his science fiction stories; if you enjoy that genre, you might want to give some of said tales a try, too: Lord of Light; This Immortal; etc.<br>
<br>
If you are into at times heavy philosophizing and prefer having to think while you read, do try out Gene Wolfe. This is not for the faint of heart, but in my personal view, the man is the greatest science fiction author still alive.  Period.  By said author: The Book of the New Sun (four books; his best work); The Fifth Head of Cerberus; The Book of the Long Sun (four books); The Book of the Short Sun (three books).<br>
<br>
If you need any more ideas, give me a tell sometime.  My shelves are loaded with books written in the English language; I'm sure I could come up with a couple of hundred suggestions, if need be. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Sir Karnos Darkmere<br>
Crusader of the 62nd Circle and 44th Alternate Advancement<br>
Lord of the Order of the Fiery  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=isesh>Isesh</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/9/03 4:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Looking for new authors</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>American Gods</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Neil Gaiman and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Microserfs</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Douglas Coupland are two that I highly recommend. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=suometar>Suometar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/10/03 5:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=27>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Looking for new authors</span><hr size=1> Some of these have been mentioned already, but here goes...<br>
<br>
American Gods by Neil Gaiman, definitely good reading.<br>
<br>
The Wraeththu trilogy by Storm Constantine (The Enchantments of Flesh and Spirit, The Bewitchments of Love and Hate, The Fulfilments of Fate and Desire).<br>
<br>
Most anything else by Storm Constantine <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
If into horror, Lost Souls by Poppy Z. Brite (also Drawing Blood, and Exquisite Corpse (not for the squeamish))<br>
<br>
Fantasy... I'm not a great fan of the Dragonlance books, but the Death Gate series by Margaret Weis and Tracy Hickman was very enjoyable.<br>
<br>
SciFi... the Gap series by Stephen R. Donaldson.<br>
<br>
Anything by Terry Pratchett.<br>
<br>
&quot;Heavier&quot; reading... Dostoyevsky. Crime and Punishment obviously, though my favorite remains The Idiot.<br>
<br>
I've never read it in English, but if a good translation exists The Divine Comedy by Dante Alighieri is worth reading. Much depends on the quality of translation - I've read two versions in Finnish and one is VERY good, while the other... not really worth mentioning. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
And thanks to Tinwin I'll have to re-read some Astrid Lindgren now. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Very good suggestion.<br>
